a black box in your car ? 
as America's road planners struggle to find the cash to mend a highway system , many see a solution in a black box that fits by the dashboard .
the devices , which track every mile and transmit that information , are a controversial attempt in state planning offices to overhaul the system for funding major roads . 
highway planning has suddenly spawned intense debate . 
libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to use the boxes to keep track of miles to draw up a tax bill . 
the tea party is aghast . 
the American Civil Liberties Union is concerned , raising privacy issues . 
while Congress can't agree on whether to proceed , several states are not waiting . 
they are exploring how they can move to a system in which drivers pay per mile of road . 
thousands of motorists have already taken the boxes for a test drive . 
this really is a must for our nation . 
" it is not a matter of something we might choose to do , " said executive director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments , which is planning to start tracking miles by California motorist by 2025 .
there is going to be a change in how we pay these taxes . 
the technology is there to do it . 
the push comes as the Highway Trust Fund , financed with taxes Americans pay at the gas pump , is broke . 
Americans don't buy as much gas as they used to .
cars get many more miles to the gallon . 
the federal tax hasn't gone up in 20 years . 
politicians are loath to raise the tax when gas prices are high . 
" the gas tax is just not sustainable , " said a transportation policy expert .
his state recently put devices on 500 cars to test out a pay-by-mile system . 
" this works out as the most logical alternative , " he said .
wonks call it a mileage-based user fee . 
the idea appeals to urban liberals , as the taxes could change driving patterns in ways that reduce congestion and greenhouse gases .
California planners are looking to the system to meet the goals in the state's global warming laws .
but chairman of the House Transportation Committee said he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative .
the free marketeers at the Reason Foundation are also fond of having drivers pay per mile .
" this is not just a tax , " said vice president of policy at Reason .
people are paying into what they are getting . 
the movement is also bolstered by two former U. S. Transportation secretaries , who in 2011 urged Congress to move in the pay-per-mile direction . 
the Senate approved a pilot project last year that would have involved about 10000 cars . 
but the House leadership killed the proposal , on concerns of rural lawmakers representing constituents whose lives involve logging lots of miles .
several states and cities are nonetheless moving ahead .
Oregon is enlisting 5000 drivers in the biggest experiment .
those drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of gas taxes . 
Nevada has already completed a pilot . 
New York City is looking into one . 
Illinois is trying it on a limited basis with trucks . 
and the I-95 Coalition , which includes 17 state transportation departments , is studying how they could .
the concept is not a universal hit . 
in Nevada , where volunteers' cars were equipped with the devices , drivers were uneasy about the government being able to monitor their every move .
" concerns about Big Brother were a major problem , " said Alauddin Khan , who directs strategic and performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation .
it was not something people wanted . 
as the trial got underway , the ACLU of Nevada warned : " it would be fairly easy to turn these devices into full fledged tracking devices . "
there is no need to build an enormous technological infrastructure that will be expanded to keep records of comings and goings . 
Nevada is among several states now scrambling to find affordable technology to keep track of miles , but not exactly where and at what time .
if you can do that , Khan said , the public gets more comfortable . 
the hunt for that technology has led some agencies to a startup called True Mileage . 
the firm was not originally in the business .
it was seeking to break into an emerging market in auto insurance , in which drivers would pay based on their mileage . 
but the devices appeal to highway planners because they don't use GPS and deliver a limited amount of information , uploaded periodically . 
" people will be more willing to do this if you do not track their speed and their location , " said chief executive of True Mileage .
there have been some mistakes in these state pilot programs . 
there are less expensive and intrusive ways . 
in Oregon , planners are experimenting with giving drivers different choices . 
they can choose a device with or without GPS . 
they can choose not to have a device , opting instead to pay a flat fee based on the average by all state residents .
other places are hoping to sell the concept by having the devices do more . 
in New York City , officials are seeking to develop a taxing device that would pay parking meter fees , provide " pay-as-you-drive " insurance , and create speed data from other drivers to avoid traffic . 
" motorists would participate because of the benefits , " says a city planning document . 
some transportation planners wonder if paying by the mile is just a giant distraction . 
at the Metropolitan Transportation Commission in the San Francisco Bay Area , officials say Congress could deal with the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund by raising gas taxes . 
an extra one-time or annual levy could be imposed on drivers of hybrids and others whose vehicles don't use much gas .
" there is no need for surgery when you need to take an aspirin , " said the commission's director of legislation and public affairs . 
if we do this , millions of drivers will be concerned about their privacy .
Mozambique security concerns mount as powerful personalities clash 
with a statue of Samora Machel , Mozambique's founding president , staring down on them , thousands of people gathered in central Maputo to chant peace slogans .
" we want peace back ; we want stability , " said Vanessa de Sousa , chief executive of an investment company . 
she swapped her corporate attire for a T-shirt emblazoned with " we demand security " as she joined the crowds on Thursday .
for two weeks , there have been daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo , some of the worst since a peace deal more than 20 years ago . 
Renamo was once a notorious rebel movement , backed by white-ruled Rhodesia and then South Africa's apartheid government to destabilise the country's independent government . 
after a 1992 peace deal , it became an opposition party . 
the country is unlikely to slide back into full-blown conflict , but recent events have unnerved foreign investors and locals .
the stakes are high for the economy as the discovery of offshore gas reserves and coal deposits could bring in more than $50bn of investment over the next few next years from companies . 
the ruling FRELIMO party , the dominant political force since 1975 , and Renamo blame each other .
RENAMO says the government initiated the latest clashes by launching an attack in Sofala province , a Renamo stronghold , on October 17 . 
assaults escalated as government forces attacked Renamo bases and attempted to kill the group's leader , Renamo's spokesman told the Financial Times . 
the government blames Renamo for attacking soldiers .
President Armando Guebuza has sought to play down concerns about instability . 
Guebuza told the French news agency on Wednesday that Dhlakama wanted to use " his forces to impose on the government his own decisions . "
both FRELIMO and Renamo insist they want to avoid war . 
but concerns have grown after Mazanga was quoted saying Renamo was abandoning the 1992 peace accord . 
he told that he meant the agreement was no longer being respected by FRELIMO . 
" our vision is to come back to negotiations , but with seriousness , " Mazanga said . 
previous talks between the parties have done little to ease tensions .
" it's two big men butting heads together , " said a lecturer at the Open University and Mozambique expert . 
neither of them are prepared to make the concessions that are necessary . 
RENAMO , which has been pushing for electoral reforms , had already said it would boycott municipal elections in November . 
presidential and parliamentary polls are scheduled for next year . 
commentators have interpreted its use of force as the attempt to win concessions and financial spoils . 
Renamo's share of the vote has been declining since 1992 , while a newer party , the Democratic Movement of Mozambique ( MDM ) , is expected to improve its showing at the elections . 
Mazanga says Guebuza - due to step down when his second term ends - wants to destroy the country's democracy . 
" he does not want multiparty democracy , he does not want transparent elections he does not want peace because he does not want to leave the presidency , " Mazanga said .
it is unclear how much capacity Renamo has , but it has carried out attacks on police stations and vehicles . 
most of the skirmishes have taken place in Sofala province , several hundred kilometres north of Maputo but hosts the port that miners rely on to export coal . 
in June , Rio suspended its use of the railway for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the line .
Mazanga was coy when asked about whether Renamo would repeat this threat . 
Renamo wanted to " warn the international community that things were not going well in Mozambique , " Mazanga said . 
instability has added to frustrations with the government , says an independent media company , with people concerned about corruption , the slow pace of development and a recent kidnappings .
" people think the ones responsible for the future of the country are the government and the president , and he should be the one to find solutions for the problems , " he says . 
a demonstrator said people just wanted stability . 
" no one cares about Renamo and FRELIMO , they just want peace again , they want free access to the roads , " he said . 
ceremony in Memory of the Cremated 
the Père Lachaise crematorium is organizing a ceremony in memory of all those cremated this year .
Anne Hidalgo , socialist candidate for Paris mayorship , is expected to attend and explain her proposals on funerary matters . 
click above to watch the ceremony . 
more and more French people are choosing cremation for their own funerals - 53 % , according to an Ipsos survey carried out among 1009 people . 
it is the opposite for the funeral of a loved one - the French prefer inhumation ( 53 % ) . 
only 15 % of those who lose a child choose cremation . 
in his book , La Mort en Cendres , Damien Le Guay , philosopher and vice-chairperson of the Comité National d'Ethique du Funéraire emphasises the " violence " that cremation represents .
there is a sense of " violence committed against the body of a loved one " , which will be " reduced to a pile of ashes " in a very short time instead of after a process of decomposition that " would accompany the stages of grief " .
there is also a " symbolic violence " that relates to the " obliteration of the person's singularity " .
why is this accepted in certain Nordic and protestant countries , but is still taken badly in France ? 
" because cremation is a recent development , " says Marie-Frédérique Bacqué , president of the Thanatological Society and author of the book Apprivoiser la Mort . 
the Catholic Church only started tolerating it in 1963 .
for François Michaud-Nérard , director general of Funerary Services for the City of Paris , getting to grips with cremation is about giving the deceased a ceremony as dignified as with inhumation .
the Ipsos survey shows the attachment to the ceremony . 
77 % of French want one for their loved ones , be it religious ( 53 % ) or civil ( 24 % ) . 
nowadays , 73 % of people choosing cremation want a ceremony . 
66 % of atheists or non-believers also want one . 
crematoria have adapted to this change .
" they have been trying to spare families from the violence in waiting followed by their being handed the ashes , " observes Michaud-Nérard . 
70 % of establishments now offer a master of ceremonies to conduct the ritual in the presence of the body : greet the congregation , mention the deceased by name , connect the deceased to those present , evoke who the person was , give sense to their death , organise a farewell . 
this is what has been happening at the Père Lachaise crematorium since 1998 . 
the masters of ceremonies are often people who have moved into this new type of employment . 
there are also former Catholic priests . 
it is in this context that , since 2010 , the crematorium has been organising memorial ceremonies , lay and non-religious , on All Saints Day , to which it invites the families of those who have been cremated during the year . 
for the second consecutive year , one of these ceremonies has been relayed online .
the crematorium has authorised us to broadcast it . 
Ukraine Close to Economic Collapse 
rating agency , Standard & Poor's , reduced Ukraine's credit rating on Friday , casting a doubt on the ability of the former Soviet republic to meet its financial obligations .
the debt rating moved to B- .
this rating is accompanied by a negative outlook , with S & P seeing at least one chance in three that it will downgrade the rating in the next year . 
" it is increasingly unlikely that the government's strategy will make it possible to sufficiently guarantee foreign currencies to meet its increased external financial commitments , " explained the American agency . 
the agency notes that Ukraine's foreign exchange reserves fell by 26 % between September 2012 and September 2013 , and the trend is expected to continue . 
this complicates the repayment of credit from abroad . 
these reserves are collapsing , leading to the agency considering devaluation more likely , which would inflate the country's foreign debt .
moreover , Kiev needs liquid assets to pay for its gas imports from Russia , which accuses it of not having paid a bill of 882 million dollars .
the announcement comes as bad news for the Ukrainian government in a period of tension with its Russian neighbour , which is furious with Kiev's willingness to sign an association agreement with the EU at the end of November . 
this was made public the day after the publication of statistics showing that the country's economy had suffered its fifth consecutive quarterly drop between July and September . 
its debt has exploded in recent years . S & P estimates it as 33.5 % of the GDP , as opposed to 10 % prior to the crisis of 2008-2009 . 
experiencing a budgetary deficit , the country has been asking for aid from the International Monetary Fund for months . the latter , in 2010 , had given the former a 15300 million dollars loan , but this time has released just 3400 million . 
the IMF is refusing to pay until the country has adopted unpopular reforms .
the IMF noted this week that " the significant need for external finance " represented " a weakness " , even though there were " signs of economic improvement " .
however , for the economist Oleksandr Joloud from the Centre for Political Studies , " no improvement can be expected in the short term " . 
" there is little hope of unpopular reforms being made in a pre-election year , " said the expert in an AFP interview . presidential elections are planned for 2015 . 
the only hope is for an improvement in international circumstances . 
S & P notes the " uncertainty " linked to the possible signing of an association agreement between Ukraine and the EU .
" signing the agreement would be good for business in the long term , but it might have negative consequences in the short term in relation to Russia's reaction , " explained S & P , concerned Moscow may introduce " trade restrictions " . 
Russia , responsible for a quarter of Ukrainian exports , has warned that if a free trade area is created it will have to reinforce its border controls for imported goods .
Ben Greenman : the Tenth Anniversary of the New York Comedy Festival : the New Yorker 
one could argue that New York City is the birthplace of standup comedy in America : nearly a hundred years ago , the vaudevillian Frank Fay served as the master of ceremonies on Broadway telling jokes directly to the crowd . 
Fay's innovation has been extended through the years , most recently by the New York Comedy Festival . 
created and overseen by Caroline Hirsch , the founder of the standup institution Carolines , the festival celebrates its tenth anniversary , with more than sixty shows .
" most of these headliners appeared at Carolines , and went on to greater success , " Hirsch said .
we built this festival as a way of continuing to work with them . 
this year's event includes appearances by Wanda Sykes , Kathy Griffin , and Bill Maher , as well as " Stand Up for Heroes , " an annual music-and-comedy benefit for military veterans , at Madison Square Garden , featuring , among others , Bruce Springsteen , Jon Stewart , Roger Waters , and Bill Cosby . 
as the festival has expanded , so has the world of comedy . 
several of the comedians participating in this year's festival came up through shows on smaller networks .
Nick Kroll rose to prominence on a deep-cable sitcom and now has his own Comedy Central sketch show . 
Jenny Slate cast member on both " Saturday Night Live " and " parks and Recreation , " is best known for her viral video series " Marcel the Shell with Shoes On . " 
both Kroll and Slate , as well as other young comedians with distinctive voices , are products of the decentralized world of American comedy . 
one of the festival's biggest draws will be an interview : David Steinberg talking to Larry David . 
Steinberg started as a standup comedian but has become television and film director , as well as an unofficial comedy historian . 
from 2005 to 2007 , he hosted a show on TV Land called " Sit Down Comedy with David Steinberg . " 
the meeting takes place in the center of Manhattan . 
" the city is definitely in the comedy DNA of all of Larry's work , " Steinberg said . 
he was telling me that sometimes he'll walk down an alley between two buildings and think to himself , Hey , if I lose all my money , maybe I'll live here . 
