Cocaine-addict lawyer who tipped off Mr Big about police investigation is jailed 
Basharat Ditta would feed information to crime lord Neil Scarbrough 
the solicitor feared his drug addiction would be exposed 
was given a three-year prison sentence 
a top defence lawyer who told a drugs Mr Big about a police investigation , because he feared his drug addiction would be exposed , has been jailed for three years . 
Basharat Ditta would feed intelligence to crime lord Neil Scarbrough about his drug trafficking activities after he became compromised by his cocaine habit . 
the solicitor was arrested at his home in 2011 following a police surveillance operation into Scarborough , who he had represented in a previous trial . 
officers spotted Sarborough dropping off three bags of cocaine at the lawyer's home in while he was out . 
inquiries revealed Ditta was a " regular user " of the Class A drug after tests  . 
over an eight month period he sought to obtain information on the arrests of two men on behalf of Scarborough as well as one of his associates . 
all four suspects were being watched by police at the time as part of a major investigation into a heroin and cocaine racket . 
they were later jailed after police seized heroin and cocaine during a series of raids . 
Ditta fed information to criminals because of fears his cocaine addiction would be exposed 
today Ditta was facing disgrace after being found guilty of two counts of perverting the course of justice following a three week trial at Liverpool Crown Court . 
he admitted cocaine possession at an earlier hearing . 
the lawyer's downfall came after police investigating Scarborough discovered he had been in phone contact with Ditta in February 2011 . 
two detectives trailed the suspect arriving at Ditta's house in and was seen to place the drugs under the lawyer's bins . 
soon after the drop off , Scarborough was in phone contact with Ditta who had been out at the dinner . 
the lawyer returned home to discover the drugs . 
the court heard Ditta was a " regular user " of cocaine after tests found traces of the Class A drug in his hair and on his credit cards 
Ditta was arrested later but denied using cocaine and and said he had been speaking to the suspected dealer because he was his client .
during his arrest Ditta picked up his wallet and tried to remove several credit cards but they were all seized and a hair sample was taken . 
in a police interview he said he ran an office at his home and clients would call at his house on legal business . 
but the court heard he would call players in the drugs supply chain after key arrests to tell them what detectives knew . 
prosecuting , Anne Whyte said : " if anyone should know not to the break the law , it is a criminal solicitor . " 
Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal solicitor . 
the relationship is not simply a drug dealer , but a drug dealer providing his lawyer with drugs . 
some of his communications will have been legitimate because he was their lawyer . 
but this went beyond the confines of a lawyer-client relationship . 
he thwarted the police's investigation to enable them to continue in their criminal activities . 
Mr Ditta was not honouring his profession , but dishonouring it . 
he got close to certain clients , in particular Scarborough . 
Ditta claimed : " if I was a corrupt lawyer , which I am not , and I wanted to feed information to Mr Scarborough , I would not wait 15 hours . " 
but after the hearing Supt Lee Halstead from Lancashire Police said : " Mr Ditta turned from criminal solicitor to a criminal himself . " 
his addiction left him compromised and vulnerable to the motives of members of organised crime groups who tasked him to obtain information regarding police investigations . 
solicitors should uphold the highest standards of integrity and should instil trust and confidence . 
Mr Ditta has betrayed this trust and attempted to hide behind the veneer of his profession . 
Lancashire's Serious and Organised Crime Unit led the investigation into Mr Ditta which has also seen him convicted of possession of cocaine and now perverting the course of justice . 
let this case serve as a warning to criminals . 
we will put you before the courts . 
