five years ago , my father passed away . 
at first , I was in denial . I spoke of him in the present tense .
I was afraid of forgetting him , or I did not know how I was going to " spend time " with him . 
there is no formula for passing through the wall of the invisible .
then signs started to appear . 
the first time I had this feeling of his presence , he was in the passenger seat while I was driving .
another time I quietly woke up and went to look at his watch . 
the smiling image of my father stays with me during my everyday activities . 
our mother left us after an fight against cancer .
that is what I thought when I saw her stiff body under the sheets of the hospital bed . 
her funeral was a cold goodbye focused on the light of candles . 
I thought she had gone . 
gradually , by way of faint appearances , she came back into my life , evolving as she took back her place in my mind .
then she revealed herself by showing me aspects of myself I had never seen before .
I learnt that I had not lost my mother , just a woman that I did not know well .
in dying , this woman had completed her life and freed the person that I loved , and now she was back . 
this detour in my life is still the most unexpected and beautiful thing .
it is a privilege that the people we love never leave us .
I am " inside and out " . 
I have always been told that . 
I never believed it at the time . 
I had a difficult relationship with him until he became old and ill . 
I was no longer afraid of him and able to love him .
one day , he died . 
for a long time , he stayed with me - when I stopped smoking , was afraid , was ill ...
he would speak to me , encourage me , he lived in my body . 
I would see his hands when I looked at mine ; I lent him my body . 
but this was never indiscreet . 
I could still lead a personal life . 
he allowed me privacy .
that lasted a long time , then one day he was gone . 
in the end , it felt comfortable to be understood , encouraged , advised .
I don't know who said that those who die are not forgotten but invisible .
my parents are no longer here but close to me constantly . 
in every event I feel their presence , always referring to them : what would they say , think , do ? 
I dream of them several times a week .
I often dream of the last moments I shared with them , except that one thing prevents me from enjoying the moment . 
I wake up distressed because it hits me and I feel their absence deeply .
dreams affect me differently , so they continue to live and be a part of my life . 
on the day before I was going to find out the gender of my baby I dreamt that I woke up and my father was waiting for me . he was smiling and was happy that I was expecting a little boy . 
the following day , I had the feeling that he had come to visit me in my dream to tell me he was sharing the joy . 
I was indeed carrying a boy . 
I loved sharing that moment with him and enjoy talking of that shared memory .
exactly five years ago , my grandmother died .
one year previously , she had travelled with my family to Cuba . 
hence the shock that provoked in the young graduate I was .
in spite of everything , I said my goodbyes quickly . 
but she continues to influence my life , particularly through hard times .
deciding to learn Arabic and pursuing an interest in the Middle East were not trivial decisions . 
I used to listen to her speak Arabic during my childhood and talk about Morocco where she had lived before coming back to France .
the values she instilled in me are still there , so I often end up wondering what she would want me to do .
it's the same with my opinions : I try to live up to the generosity and correctness of her mind . 
I feel her as a daily presence .
I see her eyes on me .
my mother died nineteen years ago .
she died after talking to me on the telephone . 
I went through all the stages : incomprehension , anger , grief , tears , anywhere , anytime . 
but time eased the pain . 
now there is just the gap , the need for her to entrust me , to reassure me . 
yet , she is there , a silent presence .
every morning I see her eyes looking at me , the dark rings giving her a burdened look , the wrinkles around the lips , the lines that mark the forehead . 
my mother has taken possession of my face , and she looks back at me in the mirror .
and every morning , I look away . 
my wife and the mother of my children died of cancer at 43 . 
we always feel her protecting us .
this was her promise on her death bed ; gradually , saying her name is no longer taboo but a comfort . 
I talk to her when the absence hurts too much , and she comes into my dreams when my spirits are low . 
we feel supported in difficult moments , and time has made us realise that she was the conductor . 
if somebody truly loved you , their absence cannot tear them out your heart . 
the person you loved becomes your inner energy . 
I lost my father on 22 August 2008 to asbestos-related cancer . 
I was very close to him , I always acted according to what he would have thought or appreciated . 
I was unable to attend his burial , and three weeks after his death gave birth to a boy . 
sometimes my beliefs are different from his , always asking myself if what I am doing conforms with his way of seeing things . 
I have even had problems at work because of these convictions . 
I can't do otherwise ; I lose sleep and constantly ask myself what he would think .
I don't know if I have adopted his way of thinking or am simply like him ? 
he will always be my point of reference . 
he was like an alter ego , we didn't even need to speak . 
in short , he is there every day .
I feel his presence and it makes me happy . 
almost thirty years ago , my husband died aged 33 . 
I was 28 and our son was 6 . 
the immense pain that engulfed me has eased , but he is still close to me . 
he often " turns up " in my dreams in a way so vivid that when I wake up I am sad again when I realise it was a dream . 
the other night , he asked how I was ; I said not good , and he said " I'm coming down " , in a voice so real that I woke up and switched on the bedside lamp and looked around , convinced that he would come . 
I live in the same house and feel he is watching me ; I turn round and see he isn't there but know it's him and I talk to him . 
I feel his presence in every room and it makes me happy . 
I wouldn't leave this house for anything . we were happy here and his spirit lives here with me . 
I'm 58 and I have always lived alone since losing him . he is and will remain the love of my life . 
I am rather sociable and have a job with responsibilities . I laugh and sing , go out , 'm a grandmother , have lots of friends , but my heart and soul belong to him . I never talk about him except with my son and never go to the cemetery .
